WEBVTT

00:06.072 --> 00:10.117
So each time we turn the tape over, then we have that 
15-second protective delay.

00:13.981 --> 00:17.485
Now, first, Professor Fleming, I'd like to know 
what interested you in the sea. Why did you choose

00:17.625 --> 00:20.148
the sea as a profession? Well, I was studying as a 
chemist at the University of British Columbia and

00:21.710 --> 00:35.185
completed my bachelor's degree in 1929 and stayed 
on at the the University of British Columbia, take

00:35.789 --> 00:41.657
a master's degree in chemistry. And this, as you 
should recognize, was the beginning of the

00:42.478 --> 00:48.886
Depression. And it was quite obvious to me that 
there were more chemists than were going to be

00:48.906 --> 01:03.805
needed, and that it was particularly difficult to 
obtain any sort of graduate degree. student

01:04.257 --> 01:15.471
support in chemistry, and I had become somewhat 
bored with the field of chemistry and thought I'd

01:04.257 --> 01:15.471
better seek some other area. And I'd grown up right 
by the water, and many of my friends were

01:16.452 --> 01:29.247
essentially marine biologists, and I happened to 
hear about this field called oceanography, and it

01:16.452 --> 01:29.247
seemed very intriguing. So I was able to obtain a 
research assistantship at Scripps Institution,

01:32.590 --> 01:39.917
Bahia, California, in 1931, down there.

01:42.680 --> 01:44.742
Had you not been to Scripps before you acquired it? 
No. In those days, one didn't travel very much, and

01:45.703 --> 01:54.292
it was a major expedition to get to Southern 
California. Actually, I went down by ship. And did

02:00.367 --> 02:04.793
you know with whom you wished to work at Scripps 
when you went? Not really. I expected to work in

02:06.436 --> 02:28.348
chemistry, and at that time the chemist at Scripps 
was Eric Moberg, and I did essentially work with

02:06.436 --> 02:28.348
him for a number of years, although I moved out of 
the field of chemical oceanography after a few

02:06.436 --> 02:28.348
years. game involved in sort of descriptive 
physical oceanography. Now, how long were you at

02:35.354 --> 02:36.636
Scripps? Well, I was there as a graduate student 
for four years, and I completed my Ph.D. in 1935,

02:37.176 --> 02:58.099
and then was kept on in sort of research capacity 
for one year just as an assistant, and then they In

02:58.670 --> 03:16.309
1936, I was appointed as an instructor on the 
faculty at Scripps, and this was at the time that

02:58.670 --> 03:16.309
Harold Fairgroup had just been appointed and came 
in as the director, which he did in September of

02:58.670 --> 03:16.309
1936. When did you first acquire the idea of the 
textbook that became the standard in the field?

03:25.417 --> 03:35.189
more or less by accident, as a lot of these things 
do, that Scripps had never had any particular

03:25.417 --> 03:35.189
program in sort of education. And when Harold 
Spherdrup came as the director, he felt that we

03:36.210 --> 03:51.289
ought to be doing more in this line, and he started 
some summer courses in in oceanography, sort of a

03:51.505 --> 04:20.871
general survey course, and he and Martin Johnson 
and I were the principal lecturers, and the

03:51.505 --> 04:20.871
Prentice Hall Publishing Company apparently 
heard about this through their grapevine and came

03:51.505 --> 04:20.871
down and suggested that we write down our lecture 
notes, and being all innocent, we said yes, we

03:51.505 --> 04:20.871
would be willing to do so. And it was out of this 
summer course in oceanography that the volume on

04:21.188 --> 04:31.007
the oceans finally appeared. It took us about 
three years to write it, and it was finished in

04:31.768 --> 04:36.678
1942. What sort of work were you doing at Scripps 
while you were there? Oh, I went down. Do you mean as

04:43.244 --> 04:45.306
a graduate student? As a graduate student and then 
always. I was sort of Jack of all trades and have

04:47.008 --> 04:54.495
been, I think, all my career. But my principal 
interest was originally in some sort of chemical

04:55.356 --> 05:12.913
work, and I did some work on the calcium carbonate 
problem, something on nutrients. and used to

05:13.619 --> 05:26.611
participate

05:13.619 --> 05:26.611
in the very limited sort of seagoing program we had 
in those days. And then in 1932, I was given a leave,

05:27.572 --> 05:42.225
in a sense, and went up to Berkeley, to the 
University of California, to get a little bit more

05:43.083 --> 05:50.534
coursework and to prepare for my general 
examinations. And when I came back to Scripps from

05:50.735 --> 06:11.166
there, early in 1933,

05:50.735 --> 06:11.166
I was told that the Navy wanted somebody to go down 
to Central America to carry out some

05:50.735 --> 06:11.166
oceanographic work on board one of the naval 
vessels. I went down and joined the USS Hannibal,

06:11.787 --> 06:36.100
which was a vessel used by the then Navy 
Hydrographic Office, and spent several months

06:11.787 --> 06:36.100
down off the west coast of Panama and Costa Rica 
doing just sort of the field routine which had

06:11.787 --> 06:36.100
already been sort of planned. And when I got back to 
La Jolla, they said, well, why don't you write up

06:40.323 --> 06:45.690
the results? And so this actually turned out to be 
my doctoral thesis and got me into sort of

06:45.931 --> 06:53.841
descriptive physical oceanography. That was 
what I was interested in, is when did you get this

06:54.442 --> 06:59.649
first descriptive oceanography that you were in 
in the early 30s? And you stayed with that, though,

07:00.591 --> 07:02.473
for two or three years. I think of you more there 
than as a chemical oceanographer. Oh, yes. I

07:06.318 --> 07:09.823
haven't really done any chemical oceanography. 
since that time, really, because as

07:10.276 --> 07:38.325
soon as I had finished up my thesis on this 
particular material, why, Dr. Sverdrup had

07:10.276 --> 07:38.325
arrived and

07:10.276 --> 07:38.325
was very anxious to start a more kind of systematic 
program of field work. And this developed in a sort

07:40.060 --> 08:09.156
of indirect way, as many of these enterprises did, 
in that the California Fish and Game Commission

07:40.060 --> 08:09.156
was at that time concerned with the problem of the 
distribution and abundance of California

07:40.060 --> 08:09.156
sardines and wanted to do some oceanographic 
work. made available to Scripps the use of a small

08:10.115 --> 08:19.746
patrol vessel called the Bluefin. And in the early 
spring, and I think it extended up into the summer

08:20.527 --> 08:37.928
of 1937, we got our first systematic series of 
observations off the Southern California coast.

08:38.785 --> 08:48.697
And this continued and so on, so we became very much 
involved in essentially the regional

08:38.785 --> 08:48.697
oceanography off the coast of California. Who 
worked in the sardine fisheries activities with

08:49.198 --> 08:52.662
you? Well, we just did a

08:53.063 --> 09:07.240
certain amount of work on conventional physical 
oceanography.

09:07.726 --> 09:11.129
a little bit of chemistry and some work on the 
plankton. We never became at that time directly

09:12.391 --> 09:35.995
involved in any of the fish studies, but the 
federal government had also become very much

09:12.391 --> 09:35.995
involved in the problem, and the two people that we 
dealt with a good deal were Alton B. Setty and

09:12.391 --> 09:35.995
Lionel Walford, both of what was then, I think, the 
Bureau of Commercial Fisheries, although they

09:36.312 --> 09:41.259
changed their names often. I'm not quite sure of 
this one. But they were very much involved in the

09:44.684 --> 09:52.254
fisheries aspect and also the state fisheries. 
And the man in the state fisheries with whom we work

09:52.354 --> 10:02.809
very closely now at USC is Richard B. Tibby. run 
across, and he came down after a year or two and

10:03.295 --> 10:18.575
actually finished his PhD at Scripps on the 
oceanography of the California coast. Now, this

10:18.595 --> 10:25.644
is really the first time the Pacific coast is being 
mapped, is when you're mapping it now in these

10:18.595 --> 10:25.644
several years. Were you surprised about certain 
things? Well, I think it's Yes and no.

10:38.953 --> 10:50.451
Because of the interest in the sardine problem, 
the region was more or less prescribed for us. And

10:50.831 --> 10:59.425
yet within that area, which extended off the 
coast, I imagine about a couple of hundred miles,

11:00.367 --> 11:18.005
They wanted considerable detail, so I think one of 
the things that was rather original was the fact

11:00.367 --> 11:18.005
that we made repeated studies on a fairly closely 
spaced network of stations. This showed details

11:18.085 --> 11:27.555
that were essentially unanticipated, 
certainly.

11:27.772 --> 11:39.407
Professor Sverdrup in particular became very 
interested in the role of upwelling as it affected

11:27.772 --> 11:39.407
these waters to the south of Point Conception. And 
I think we had some of the first evidence on the

11:39.427 --> 11:51.383
existence of eddies in the area that these sort of 
features had not been identified before.

11:54.940 --> 11:58.908
Who was joining you in Scripps between, let's say, 
35 on? You seem to have a whole series of people come

11:58.928 --> 12:02.976
in at Scripps about this time who go on. Well, the 
biggest change has occurred,

12:03.838 --> 12:13.658
I feel, in about 1920. which was just about the time 
I went there as a graduate student, and that Dr.

12:14.667 --> 12:42.750
Vaughn, who was the director, had been able to get 
some additional funds, and he had a really very

12:14.667 --> 12:42.750
imaginative sort of view of what ought to be done at 
that time, and he added two faculty people, and

12:43.810 --> 12:54.601
Claude Zobel in microbiology, and Dennis Fox 
essentially in physiology and biochemistry.

12:56.082 --> 13:02.028
This represented a major kind of shift in what was 
going on at Scripps. In the physical area and the

13:02.288 --> 13:11.117
field work where There were no sort of major 
additions to the

13:11.553 --> 13:31.996
faculty and staff, except during these years we 
had considerable support from people who were

13:11.553 --> 13:31.996
provided to the institution under the WPA, the 
Works Progress Administration. One of the

13:33.318 --> 13:39.805
curious things is that the illustrations in my 
thesis were all drawn by man whose background had

13:40.730 --> 13:55.825
been in architecture and was being supported on 
these federal funds, and all my graphs looked like

13:40.730 --> 13:55.825
architectural drawings. But we had considerable 
staff support, technician support in those days

13:55.845 --> 14:07.277
from people who were assigned to scripts under the 
WPA program. Gene LaFond was one person who worked

14:08.118 --> 14:17.127
very closely with this program, with and I. And 
that was about it. Things weren't quite as large as

