It's been suggested to me recently that one of the 
problems with the modern oceanographers is they

17:12.405 --> 17:17.814
don't get their feet wet, so to speak. They don't 
spend enough time on vessels. Would you agree with

17:19.397 --> 17:20.118
that? Well, yes and no. I think the

17:27.597 --> 17:47.445
character of the work at sea has changed as the 
vessels have become much larger and as the

17:27.597 --> 17:47.445
equipment has become much more complex, and that 
the vessel we had and the the times I'm talking

17:47.763 --> 18:14.175
about prior to the sardine surveys was just called 
the scripts and she was a 55 foot trawler type

17:47.763 --> 18:14.175
vessel with a one man permanent crew and so the 
graduate students in general used to take out and

17:47.763 --> 18:14.175
run the ship essentially navigate as necessary do 
all of the sampling do all of the sort of deckhand

18:14.999 --> 18:24.251
functions, as well as work on the samples after 
they were back in the laboratory. Now it's more

18:24.271 --> 18:38.029
like, I have the feeling, as a graduate student 
goes out, it's more or less like going on an ocean

18:24.271 --> 18:38.029
liner, that they're just, in a sense, kind of a 
passenger on a big, relatively large vessel. They

18:38.109 --> 18:42.475
have very little to do with the planning or with the 
navigation, the operation of the vessels at sea,

18:42.758 --> 18:54.676
and usually don't know very much about what's 
going on except the specific sort of project

18:42.758 --> 18:54.676
they're engaged in. So I think we've lost 
something in this process, and

18:55.077 --> 19:08.057
there's still some, I think, activities of the 
type that I'm reminiscing about that are

19:08.341 --> 19:17.933
conducted in some nearshore work at various 
institutions. But still, I find the students have

