the 30s, was there sort of a sense of excitement 
about moving out towards a new frontier? No, I

25:40.584 --> 25:42.246
don't think so. It was all good fun, but we didn't 
see any great manifest destiny or anything for We

25:50.371 --> 25:55.138
didn't think in terms of national ocean policy and 
so on. We just thought there were interesting

25:55.299 --> 25:59.665
scientific problems to be solved. And as I look 
back on it now, that period really before the war at

25:59.685 --> 26:18.775
Scripps, we were very much in sort of ivory tower, 
although as I've already indicated, we were

25:59.685 --> 26:18.775
beginning to move into what might be called 
applied oceanography as it was related to some of

25:59.685 --> 26:18.775
these fisheries problems. But ordinarily, 
though, this is still primarily research for its

26:19.700 --> 26:26.513
own sake rather than sort of the applied research 
that comes out between 1941 and 1945? Oh,

26:26.653 --> 26:30.661
yes. The funding of the institution at that time, 
the Scripps Institution, was basically all

26:39.393 --> 27:03.426
through the University of California, since the 
state funds reaching us through the university,

26:39.393 --> 27:03.426
except that in connection with the sardine 
investigations,

26:39.393 --> 27:03.426
the federal fisheries agency did provide money to 
